      <hedline>
        <hl1>Race and Democracy</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Letter from Graham Boyd (ACLU Drug Policy Litigation Project) scores US war on drugs and national frenzy of incarceration as part of the legacy of Jim Crow</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>A June 4 Week in Review article rightly questions the legitimacy of supposedly democratic elections from Peru to Iran that ''don't guarantee free expression or fair treatment of minorities.''</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>A June 4 Week in Review article rightly questions the legitimacy of supposedly democratic elections from Peru to Iran that ''don't guarantee free expression or fair treatment of minorities.''</p>
        <p>But what we condemn abroad flourishes unacknowledged at home, where the war on drugs and a national frenzy of incarceration deprive nearly four million citizens of their voting rights. Racial bias in law enforcement means that blacks are seven times as likely as whites to be disfranchised under felony voter laws.</p>
        <p>Jim Crow and poll taxes may exist only as a memory, but the legacy of systemic denial of voting rights persists and grows.</p>
        <p>GRAHAM BOYD  New Haven, June 5, 2000</p>
        <p>The writer is director of the A.C.L.U. Drug Policy Litigation Project.</p>
      </block>
